[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Hibernate and Querydsl**\n\nI'm reflecting on compiling the source with HibernateAnnotationProcessor and asserting the generated Q class. Dynamic access looks good in the processor configuration, and it seems like there's no need for a stub here, which feels idiomatic. I wonder if there could be potential issues with JavaCompiler in a native image, particularly regarding source generation, given that the existing test did that. I want to ensure that everything runs under 60 seconds. Querydsl processor might handle scanning and generating, so that seems alright.\n\n**Clarifying native image classpath**\n\nI'm considering the problem of native images not having a JAR file classpath. In a native-image test, it seems that dependencies rely on the image heap/classes rather than the filesystem's classpath. So if the JavaCompiler is compiling code that imports these dependencies into a native executable, it could fail to locate them because there are no classpath entries available. This definitely requires careful handling of dependencies when working with native images!\n\n**Evaluating Hibernate Dependencies**\n\nI need to ensure that Class.forName has access to the necessary Hibernate classes during test runtime. To do this, I’ll add the hibernate-core dependency. It looks like the JPAConfiguration class will need JPA, likely through hibernate-core. Although Hibernate 5.6 relies on javax.persistence-api 2.2, the test source might not be importing JPA. We may also need to define annotation arguments and load javax.persistence classes through hibernate-core, possibly with an explicit inclusion of jakarta.persistence-api. That seems wise.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_02e09efad86dd3ce016a02d769e6b081a3bee79cd5527c6bc4\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqAteJcm1SnJBAVs8CfK85ZZ4kSyel6DY2pC9KizibJlRttvQM1z6ffAMJLomlM5DPjtElHTcYDhb